column8: I definitely used angle and sarcasm, and the two connections. I feel like sarcasm and angle are the most significant part of the art of joke crafting. The two connections are pretty important as well because if you only have one connection, for example, the reader might be lost on what the joke is referencing.
column12: I think seeing examples of other people's humor was more useful to me than the breaking up and explanations of the jokes. But I might be wrong about that. column8: Yes! I used the associations a lot, I found them really helpful for finding a new angle or a way to be sarcastic because I could very quickly put the headline in a new context and contrast it with things that might make it seem ridiculous. I used the violations because I knew that I had two choices -- helped to narrow it down and make it feel manageable. I used the expected reactions and expected beliefs because they helped me to be sarcastic more intentionally - I could use them to make sure the jokes violated expectations.
column12: Before, I was trying to think, I know there is something funny here...especially about the primate. But I was at a loss. I felt that I could express my own sense of humor better, even though I was using general techniques.
